Here is a shorten version of our newest YouTube video on a deadlift technique warm-up.

Do you want to see more of these types of videos? 

Deadlift Technique Warm-Up 
Go through a 4 step technique warm-up with Matt, grab a PVC or empty barbell and follow along. 

Step 1 
Getting in a good set-up. Use these 5 focal points to dial in your set-up. 
*Place the feet by hopping and land naturally.
*Set your weight distribution by rocking to heels, rocking to toes, and find your center.
*Tighten your core by squeezing your butt, and tightening your abs (use a forceful exhale). 
*Set your grip by swinging your thumbs pass the legs, close the grip. 
*Engage the back by pulling the bar against the body.

Step 2
Follow along for 5 reps. 
Hinge at the hip setting the back position and take the bar to the middle of the knee. 
 -Send the butt back, but keep knee over ankle.

Step 3 
Follow along for 5 reps.
Do step 2 + take the bar down to the shin.
 -Focus on proper knee bend.

Step 4 
Follow along for 5 reps.
From a standing position take out the pauses and descend to shin. Then deadlift without any pauses. 
 -Focus how much to push the knee back as you stand. 
 -Keeping the back flat. 
 -Keeping the bar against the body.

It’s time for a new training cycle. 

June 19 to August 19 (with an additional two weeks of deload).
The focus will be:
1) Single leg stamina/stability
2) Pressing hypertrophy 
3) Zone 2 mixed modality
4) Abs

This “focus” means that these elements will be seen more regularly in the microcycle template than you would normally see in a general fitness program. In addition to our subscriber’s request for these elements, we are prepping for hiking/hunting/combat challenge real-world endeavors in the fall.

We will also be adding opportunities to use sandbags and sleds if you have them (or want to buy one). If you’re looking to add to your equipment compliment, consider a sandbag with handles and/or a Strongman Sandbag. We will also provide opportunities to use a multi-function sled like the Rogue Slice Sled.

@train_ftw 
-
Outwork. Unhustle. 
-
We don’t believe in the hustle culture. We believe in a playful life, but a playful life without hard work is disappointing. It’s the discipline and the hard work that make the play more joyful, more grateful and more free. 
-
So we believe in outworking and unhustling. Work hard. Then play joyfully. Put in your best effort, then do something you enjoy that fills you up. 
-
Of the few things we have found to be true, this one is an unintentional ethos. 
-
Discipline matters, hard work matters, but so does rest, so does play, so does love. 
-
#denver #GORUCK #bubsnaturals #trainftw #adventure #fitness #firstresponders #firefighterlife #outwork #unhustle #unhustlemovement #roguefitness

The Long Game.

Outwork. Unhustle is all about the long game. Our mission is to be a tool to strengthening our people for a life of adventure. We can’t experience the greatest joys without taking care of ourselves. We all know it. If we don’t train our body, we’ll never reach the potential of our life experiences. It’s like brushing our teeth. It’s the core, it’s the heart and it’s a gift. 

We have to work on our body, we have to tend to our minds and we have to nourish ourselves in a way that gives our family, friends and selves the best possible future. While we love aesthetics (not gonna lie), we recognize our own vanity and our egos push for performance. However, our north star is the future. Quality of life and longevity. It’s the experiences of life. It’s the people in our lives. It’s a life full of capacity. Refuse to be the liability. 

Do the work and take the time to play, because it’s the long game that matters. 

#denver #trainftw #adventure #fitness #firstresponders #longgame #outwork #unhustle #garagegym

Garage gym conditioning inspiration: 

Every minute on the minute for 20:00, perform:
Even: 5 Power cleans and jerks (medium)
Odd: 5 Burpees + 5 toes to bar + 5 burpees

Medium is relative to each person, but the idea is that you can link 5 reps unbroken fairly easily. It’ll make you breathe and spike your rate, but you can manage the weight.

However, the 5+5+5 will be difficult to complete in the minute. Try to keep an interval goal, like 5 burpees in 0:20, 0:05 rest, 5 toes to bar in 0:10, 0:05 rest, and 5 more burpees in 0:20. 

Tough but “fun”.

Been having knee problems most of the spring. It’s been a bummer to be so limited, but it’s also been nice to switch gears and let off the throttle a bit. Problem is - I feel like I have nothing to focus on. Nothing I can charge into and achieve.
-
I have always chased the next bigger and more exciting thing, whether it was a PR, a longer ride, or a bigger objective. I’ve come to learn that I may not have high enough levels of dopamine in the regions of the brain that regulate attention.
- 
In college, I think that I may have subconsciously decided that pursuing recreational activities and sport that not only require high levels of focus, but that also rewarded my efforts with elevated levels of dopamine, those activities allowed me to feel normal… happy… focused.
-
When I look back at the moments in life I am most proud of, that I felt the most fulfillment, they were these moments of extreme effort, working through dangerous activity, achieving something I had trained hard for. These moments I was focused, free of distraction, and tuned in.
-
I was diagnosed with ADHD in 1990 (7th grade)… I know that’s crazy. If you are in a similar boat or if you have kids that are - get them outside! Have them try something that gets them away from the screens. Do something that they can work up to with you. The reward is the effort and the heightened focus you never knew you had inside of you.
-
In my experience, it feels like those moments of laser focus and pleasure last for a while after the experience itself.
-

What is RPE and why use it? 

Your rate of perceived exertion is a subjective assessment of how physically and mentally difficult an exercise is for you.

* Aerobic endurance (2-3) Can maintain for hours and carry on a conversation. 
* Speed/ V02 Max (6-7) Uncomfortable. Short of breath and can only speak a few words or a sentence. 
* Neuromuscular power (10): At your physical limit or past it, and only maintain for seconds. Can’t talk/can barely remember your name. 

There is a lot of fancy ways to track how you’re training. This one is fairly simple and requires no extra “gear”.

A RPE scale is universally applicable to training athletes and it can be used to better understand the INTENT of a training session, as well as a REMINDER while training whether you’re achieving the intended stimulus.

What’s your experience with an RPE scale?

Min 2: 10/10 Bulgarian split squats

Have a tough time getting through the first minute in your cold plunge? Me too.
-
The practice that gets me through the tough part is:
3 rounds of:
0:04 slow inhale
0:04 lungs full hold
0:08 slow exhale
0:04 lungs empty hold
-
That’s 1:00 and usually enough time to settle your sympathetic nervous system down and to allow you to sit for the remainder of your session. I like to do 3x/week for 5:00/session pre-workout.
-

Coming from a place of being overwhelmed, it can be really hard to focus and just get the work done. Especially, if that isn’t your jam, ADHD included. 

An effective concept we recently employed was the “workcation”. Take a few days away from home, plan each days work hours. Now plan 1-3 hours of movement/activities. For us, this was 4-6 hours of computer work accompanied with 1-3 hours of outdoor time, climbing, hiking and hunting. It motivated us to sit down and focus when we needed to and it also helped us integrate the #outwork and #unhustle lifestyle. 

Now we can’t do this every week or even every month, but now that it’s on our radar, we’ll be doing it when we can. 

Any other idea’s on how to incorporate intentional focused work with fun?

Yes, we are loyal enthusiasts of the UNHUSTLE. Because enjoying your time while on this planet matters. But that doesn’t mean it’s easy.

We have to get after it, so we can get after it. 

Outwork, but unhustle. 

If you’re a recovering or current workaholic, easier said than done. But.. we aren’t going to be wishing we had spent more hours at work, are we? 🤷🏻‍♀️

Here are three things that help us:
💥List 1-3 things a day that will make you feel accomplished if you get them done. 
💥Schedule time each week to do what you enjoy, preferably with people you love❤️.
💥Schedule time to take care of your health everyday.

We struggle with distractions, and distractions rob us of our lives. These three things help us stay focused on what’s important and quiets the overwhelming voice that tells us the to-do list is never done. 

❓How do you make sure you’re enjoying this life?

-
Not trying to make up for lost time.
-
Not jumping on a restrictive diet.
-
Not in the mindset of “I have to”, instead “I get to.”

If you’re starting a new program… here’s a suggestion: don’t look for a competitive program. Don’t look for what’s going to get you in shape fast. Don’t look for a program that’s something you were successful with years ago.
-
Look for something that leaves you wanting more, but that you really enjoy doing. Be consistent, be be consistent.

The shoulder can be fragile, like the back and knees. This is why it’s important to prep them prior to shoulder intensive work. Here are 5 tried a true shoulder priming exercises to get your shoulders ready for the dirty work! 

Shoulder Priming 
10x Supinated A, 2 count hold 
10x Supinated T, 2 count hold 
10x 90º/90º External rotations, 2 count hold, + press, + slow lower
5x Snow angles, slow
5x Scapular wall slide, slow

All exercises can be completed with crossover symmetry style tube bands, exercise bands or change plates on a bench.
